Thanks for the detailed report! The issue is that `System.Timers.Timer.Elapsed` fires on a **ThreadPool thread**, and iOS's UIKit requires all UI operations (including `SetNeedsDisplay()`, which `InvalidateSurface()` calls under the hood) to run on the **main thread**. Android's `View.Invalidate()` handles background thread calls internally, which is why it works there.

**Workaround** — dispatch to the main thread before calling `InvalidateSurface()`:

```csharp
// MAUI
var timer = new System.Timers.Timer(1000);
timer.Elapsed += (s, e) => MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(() => skiaView.InvalidateSurface());
timer.Start();

// Or use a MAUI dispatcher timer that fires on the main thread:
Dispatcher.StartTimer(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1), () =>
{
    skiaView.InvalidateSurface();
    return true; // keep repeating
});
```

We're also investigating whether SkiaSharp should add automatic main-thread marshaling in the iOS handler to make `InvalidateSurface()` consistent across platforms.
